<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-20T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-20T12:00:00-05:00" n="150" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d150">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/9493</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-20T18:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 20, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 21, 2.55
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4521. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 284. The following is translation of a memorandum which the
                                Italian delegate on the Paris black-listing committee handed the
                                committee at the meeting of July 19: <pb facs="0199" n="1033" xml:id="pg_1033"/>
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>The Italian Government declares that it has no objection to
                                        Japan’s participating with the Allies in the formation of
                                        their black lists. It believes that it is preferable,
                                        however, to have the information concerning the Far East
                                        concentrated in Washington, following the procedure adopted
                                        for America. The creation of black lists for China should
                                        have the effect of doing away with the white lists.</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <p>For your confidential information. The French enthusiastic about
                                having a Japanese delegate on the Paris committee. Please advise
                                your views in connection therewith. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>